als that point the same way: (1) ICE certified inventories are at a fresh 7-month high (a hard availability signal), (2) demand-side evidence is weak with Europe Q4 2025 grindings down to a 12-year low and an additional reported drop in cocoa division volumes, and (3) the balance framing in the supply-chain report references projected global surpluses, which is directionally consistent with the inventory build and recent monthly price weakness. In contrast, the Permabull’s core case relies heavily on mean-reversion from the large gap to the 200-day SMA and on interpreting contango and net shorts as bullish “powder keg” setups. Those are conditional, reflexive catalysts (they require a trigger), while the bear’s cited inventory/demand data are already present.\n\nOn the ‘priced-in’/trend checks: the market is only slightly down over 24h (-0.31%) and up over 5 days (+1.33%), but that short-term stabilization does not outweigh the more structural signals in this packet (inventory build + weak grindings + bearish positioning). Also, RSI near the low-40s is explicitly not an oversold/overbought extreme in the Sentiment Report, so the bull’s “imminent squeeze” claim lacks a technical trigger from the provided indicators.\n\nEvidence counting favors the bear on independent lines: inventories (Inventory/Sentiment/Volatility reports), demand (Supply Chain + Inventory reports), and positioning (Sentiment report) all align. The bull’s strongest points (net shorts, range-bound regime, mean reversion vs SMA, contango) largely cluster around market structure/positioning rather than introducing new fundamental tightening evidence. The Agronomist also frames rainfall optimism and policy actions (COCOBOD payments) as forward-looking and explicitly flags that the physical deficit risk persists—i.e., it does not deliver a clean bullish fundamental today.\n\nVolatility cost awareness: the Volatility Report characterizes options as “rich” with elevated but compressing IV; that doesn’t f